article.headline: Wizards snap two-game skid
article.linkText: Hughes' layup lifts Wizards over Blazers
article.story:
PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Larry Hughes saw his chance and took it. His driving layup with 10.4 seconds left gave the Washington Wizards a 81-80 victory over Portland on Tuesday night. "I was just looking to drive and kick at first, but I saw an opening down the middle and took it," Hughes said. Etan Thomas' hook shot pulled the Wizards to 80-79 with 36.5 seconds left, before Hughes' layup for the final margin. After a timeout, Portland guard Jeff McInnis missed a driving layup. Hughes was all over McInnis. "Coach made a great change on that last shot putting Larry on Jeff and making him shoot a tougher shot since he had been scoring over our smaller guards," Washington guard Brevin Knight said. Hughes finished with 22 points to lead Washington, which was without top scorer Gilbert Arenas. Arenas was placed on the injured list earlier Tuesday because of a severe abdominal sprain. He was hurt Sunday in a loss at Seattle. Thomas added 12 points. Zach Randolph had 24 points and 15 rebounds for his eighth double-double this season for the Blazers. Randolph's mom was in the crowd as Portland's six-game winning streak at the Rose Garden was snapped. "It's really disappointing," he said. "I don't know what to say. It's a disappointing loss. I'm upset. We didn't win the game." Arenas, who leads the Wizards with averages of 20.8 points and 5.1 assists a game, will miss at least five games. And Washington is already missing Jerry Stackhouse, who has yet to play this season because of a knee injury. "A lot of guys have had to step up and shoulder the load," Wizards guard Chris Whitney said. "Larry Hughes did a good job. He's been carrying the load all year." The Wizards, who snapped a two-game losing streak, opened the fourth quarter with an 9-2 run to take a 68-60 lead. They couldn't extend it further, and the Blazers closed to 72-71 on McInnis' jumper. The Blazers took their first lead on the quarter with 2:37 to go, when Qyntel Woods' fast-break layup made it 76-74, and the Blazers clung to the lead until the final seconds. "They took control of the game in the fourth quarter and then we came back and we had a chance to score by scoring down the middle and either scoring or getting fouled," Portland coach Maurice Cheeks said. "But it didn't happen." The Blazers led by 18-11 midway through the first quarter but the Wizards chipped away, going up 23-22 on Hughes' 3-pointer. Knight's steal and Juan Dixon's resulting fast-break layup tied it for Washington at 32-32, before another layup by Dixon briefly put the Wizards ahead. But the Blazers took off an 11-0 run capped by Damon Stoudamire's 3-pointer and Randolph's layup, and Portland went on to lead 47-43 at the break. Both sides wrestled with the lead throughout the third quarter, and when the Blazers fell behind 59-55 on Thomas' dunk, a fan in the crowd shouted at Cheeks to put Randolph back in. "I've got to rest him sometime," Cheeks shrugged back. McInnis added 19 points and five assists for Portland.

Game notes
It was the first game back at home for Portland's Bonzi Wells since he came off his two-game suspension for cursing at coach Maurice Cheeks in a loss to Dallas. Wells, who did not start, was met by a smattering of boos from the crowd when he entered the game late in the first quarter. Wells' first game back was Saturday at Golden State, where he also played off the bench. ... Despite their strong record at home, the Blazers are 0-5 on the road. ... The Wizards won their second straight at the Rose Garden after a losing streak of eight games in Portland.
